The UV–visible absorption and emission spectra were presented in Fig. 5a. The synthetic N, S-CDs solution exhibited two absorption bands at the wavelengths around 275 and 323nm, The absorption peak at 275nm corresponded to π–π* of CC and the absorption at 323nm was ascribed to n–π* transition of the CO bond [41]. As observed from other carbon-based quantum dots, the N, S-CDs also showed excitation dependent PL under the excitation wavelength from 340 to 500nm (Fig. 6
                        ). With the excitation wavelength of 300–340nm the maximum emission wavelength remained constant. While the excitation wavelength was over 340nm, the fluorescence emission of the N, S-CDs was excitation-dependent. Specifically, with the increase of the excitation wavelength, the fluorescence peak was red shifted and the peak intensity decreased. The maximum fluorescence emission intensity can be acquired at 450nm under excitation wavelength of 390nm (Fig. 5b). Such excitation-dependent PL behavior attributed to the existence of a number of surface emissive traps as well as the different morphologies of the materials [42]. Just as FT-IR investigation, there were multiple C-, N-, O- and S-containing functional groups on the surface of the N, S-CDs leading to different surface states with various energy levels and many emissive traps. The color of the diluted N, S-CDs aqueous solution was brown yellow under ambient daylight but emitted strong blue light (450nm) when was excited with a 365nm lamp (Fig. 5, inset). Using quinine sulfate as the standard, the quantum yield of the N, S-CDs was calculated to be 35.2% (n
                        =5, RSD<1.08%), which was higher than that of the CDs only using EDTA as precursor (QY=17.2%) prepared by hydrothermal method. Moreover, no obvious fluorescence intensity change was observed for those N, S-CDs solution even being kept for 6 months at 4°C, suggesting the good stability of the CDs.
